<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-23T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-23T13:00:00-05:00" n="689" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d689">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00 Revolutions/61: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WS1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Whitehouse</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-23T11:00:00-07:00">January
                                    23, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 1:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>7. International Railway authorities have just informed me that
                            Communists attacked and are in possession of Sonsonate; they failed in
                            attempt on Ahuachapán. Salvadoran Government sending troop[s] but
                            English railway torn up so they cannot reach Sonsonate before noon.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_WS1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Whitehouse</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>